Extracting Data from Raster

Cole Tanigawa-Lau

Raster files divide data into congruent cells spread over space, creating a grid of points with continuous values, like pixels of an image. The precision (or resolution) of the raster data depends on the size of these grid cells. For a given area, smaller cells means more data, and like any other high-resolution image, raster files are often very large. The raster package is able to process raster files without loading them into memory by performing functions on chunks of the data at a time.

Loading a raster into an R object stores only information about the raster file, keeping your RAM available for other things.

Shapefiles store geographic information in vector format as points, lines or polygons. The maptools, rgeos, and rgdal packages provides a host of functions useful for reading, creating, manipulating, and analyzing shapefiles.

const <- readShapeSpatial("~/Google Drive/pak/national-constituency-boundary/National_Constituency_Boundary.shp")

The structure of shapefiles stored in R is fairly complex (try printing str(const) . . .), and for a full description you should check out the sp package vignette. To put it simply, these objects consist of features, or shapes, with data about them stored in different slots. You index these slots using @. The most important slots (for this exercise and for spatial analysis more generally) are @proj4string, which defines the objects geographic projection, and @data, which holds a data frame object. Each row of this data frame corresponds to a feature in the spatial geometry. So in this example, every row contains data about a single constituency in Pakistan. You can index these spatial geometries as you would a data frame.

Notice that the coordinate reference system above is currently NA. Unfortunately, readShapeSpatial() will not look into the associated projection file. We need to set the projection manually (or use the slower readOGR() function from rgdal) before using const in conjunction with any other spatial object. You can find out what projection to use by opening the .prj file in any text editor. Whenever you perform a function on two spatial objects, be sure they are in the same projection!

proj4string(const) <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0"
identicalCRS(pop10adj, const)
## [1] TRUE

Extracting the data from a raster is actually very simple with the packages weve loaded. It can take a long time, though. The result is a matrix with one column and a number of rows equal to the number of features in const. We can bind this matrix to the data frame stored in const2@data, replace the slot contents, and save the final product as either a .rds file or a new shapefile.

pop10adj_const <- extract(x = pop10adj, y = const, fun = mean, na.rm = TRUE)
const@data <- data.frame(const@data, pop_10adj = pop10adj_const, log_pop10adj = log1p(pop10adj_const))

saveRDS(const, "~/Google Drive/pak/const2/const2.rds")
writeSpatialShape(const, "~/Google Drive/pak/const2/const2.shp")

To repeat this process for multiple raster files, I would recommend writing code to use the extract() function for each raster, then running all of those lines overnight. If you want to check that your code worked, the easiest way might be to plot the data on a map and check that it corresponds to what you know about Pakistans population density. Ill use the logged population density variable so that we can see some variation. For a more complete introduction to visualizing shapefiles with, check out the tidyverse wiki on GitHub or Robin Lovelaces more lengthy tutorial.
